THE community alerted cops and they quickly bust a suspect, who led them to a shallow grave. But this time it wasn’t a missing person’s corpse, as is usually the case when thugs bury something.The grave was filled with stolen firearms!if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The weapons – all 15 of them – were part of 18 firearms stolen from a security company in December.Police in Thohoyandou, Limpopo, told Daily Sun the firearms were recovered on Monday after police received a tip-off.“A 22-year-old suspect was arrested and investigations led police to a house at Tswinda Village, where the firearms were found hidden in a shallow grave,” said Limpopo police spokesman Motlafela Mojapelo.The firearms included 15 pistols, seven firearm magazines and seven live rounds of ammunition.He said the weapons brought to 16 the number of firearms recovered since the robbery last year. The other firearm was recovered last year, a day after the burglary was reported, when a 24-year-old man was bust during a business robbery in Malamulele.Two of the firearms have not been found, but police hope to recover them soon.Provincial police commissioner General Nneke Ledwaba told the People’s Paper: “This co-operation by community members made sure that these firearms were removed from the hands of the criminals.” All the recovered firearms will be sent for ballistic tests to check if they were used in criminal activities elsewhere.The suspect was kept in custody after he appeared briefly in the Thohoyandou Magistrates Court on Wednesday. The case was postponed for further investigations.